In parallel to the parliamentary hearings, which were concluded today by the Congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected the public hearing to the regulations that develop the new law, with a view to both coming into force before the end of the year.
Party leaders have consistently highlighted the efforts of MPs and Senators to negotiate and agree the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the operators needed for the effective functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which is governed by the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will make it possible to provide financial advice services to both specialist firms and to individuals with legal entities, and creates a new type of financial services (ESIS) firms, financial advisory companies (AFIs) to join with securities, securities intermediate brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the performance of operations with financial instruments is being expanded by adding to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and command internalisation systems to compete with current stock exchange brokers.
The law further obliges investment service firms to disseminate information on the market of key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and the ways of coping with risk, and requires a statement of all operations performed to facilitate the supervision by the CNMV.
During the hearing in the Commercial Commission of Congress, several modifications were included, among which the latter stands out, to be considered a "complex" financial instrument given the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the US with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
