These are not Warhol's boxes
The one who combines the expressions of Sweden and the wooden crates does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
The wooden crates produced in Sweden currently cast the list of Warhol's works with dark shadows.
Most of his list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are forges.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" expressed doubts about the authenticity of the Warhols's "Brillo Boxes" of 1968, the internal research of the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm comes with a result that brought about disillusionment; the six "Brillo Boxes" which were donated by its former director, Pontus Hultén, in a gift from the Moderna Museum in 1995, are copies - as are most of the other "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type, which are in circulation on the international art market.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of art and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the reddish-dry design of the paper boxes of Brillo's soapy powder.
The exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 performed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo cottages of the carton. These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their designs, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brillo crates in Sweden, but these are not on display in Moderna Museet.
The witnesses at the time now speak of the fifteen crates that rightly entered the art and auction history at the time as the authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxy" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 it was made and displayed in Sweden with about a hundred crates, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultene boxes were only made in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg in 1990.
By then, Warhol was three years dead.
In addition to the six Brillo booths owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the top Conservator Moderna Museet, explored three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and, after their plywood boards were painted in the base and rim, were colored with oil white.
On the contrary, it emerged from the 1990 copy structure that the colour was applied to the coating without a previous basic coating directly to the plywood board - in addition, it is an acrylic and not an oil colour.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo Boxing list," said the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six rafts from his exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies"."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into these "fright-left accusations" that had been raised in the matter of boxes of soapy powder.
